Command blockers.

A command blocker is an invisible, silent zone that restricts which slash commands the player can run while they stand inside it. Place one over an area and, depending on its mode, it either blocks a chosen list of commands or allows only that list while blocking everything else. The player gets no announcement that a blocker is present — a blocked command simply refuses to run as though it were never typed. Command blockers are the way to fence off parts of a map where certain commands shouldn't work, such as keeping the player from teleporting out of an arena or spawning items during a challenge.

How a command blocker works.

A command blocker fills a rectangular area and watches the player's position. While the player is anywhere inside its footprint, every slash command they try to run — whether typed into the console, fired from a macro, or triggered by a switch or sensor — is checked against the blocker's command list before it runs. Outside the footprint the blocker has no effect at all. On 3d maps the blocker is volumetric, applying only between its minimum and maximum height.

A blocker has no sound and no presence the player can sense directly; its only effect is on which commands succeed. Several blockers can overlap, and each one applies independently, so a command is stopped if any blocker the player is standing in would stop it. To restrict commands for both of two different systems in the same spot, place two overlapping blockers.

Command blocker fields.

The command blocker form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangular area the blocker covers.

Commands. The list of slash commands the blocker acts on, checked off from the full command list. What this list means depends on the whitelist setting below.

Enable whitelist (checkbox). When unchecked, the blocker runs in blacklist mode; when checked, it runs in whitelist mode. The two modes are described below.

Blacklist and whitelist modes.

A command blocker can operate in blacklist and whitelist modes:

Blacklist (whitelist unchecked): Only the listed commands are blocked. All other commands remain enabled.
Whitelist (whitelist checked): Only the listed commands are allowed. All other commands are blocked.

See the commands topic for the full list of slash commands you can choose from, and for how command stacking and delays behave.

Authoring command blockers by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a command blocker is written under the name cblocker: cblocker minx maxx miny maxy command, command, ... whitelist. On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: cblocker minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz command, command, ... whitelist. The commands are a comma-separated list of slash command names without the leading slash, and whitelist is the literal word true for whitelist mode or false for blacklist mode.
